            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being twelve, in his father\u2019s Minnesota workshop. The air was thick with the scent of pine. His father didn't speak, just held up two pieces of wood. He slid them together, and they locked into a perfect dovetail joint, seamless and strong. In that quiet moment, Erik understood. It wasn't about decoration; it was about inherent integrity. The system worked. That silent lesson became the foundation for everything he would later build, both with his hands and in his career, and occurred when he was in his early teens.\n\n2.\nIt was 2000. From his spartan SOMA apartment, he watched a dot-com launch party raging in the warehouse across the street\u2014irrational exuberance made manifest. He, meanwhile, was mapping a shipping route for ball bearings. He felt no envy, only a strange sense of calm. He knew their system was built on hope, while his was built on physics. When their lights went out months later, his shipments were still on time. That moment, early in his San Francisco tenure, confirmed his pragmatic path: build things that last.\n\n3.\nThe ink on the divorce papers was figuratively dry when he first stood alone in his empty Dogpatch condo. The silence wasn\u2019t peaceful; it was a vacuum. For a man who managed systems, his most personal one had just collapsed. But as the evening light faded over the shipyards, a new feeling took root: not despair, but a quiet mandate. He was now the sole engineer of his own contentment. This turning point in his late thirties was daunting, but the blueprint was finally his to draw.\n\n4.\nCresting Potrero Hill on his bike one evening in his early forties, lungs burning, he was stopped by the view. The fog wasn't a blanket; it was an engine, a slow-motion machine rolling in, shrouding the port cranes. The physical effort, the cool air, the industrial vista\u2014it all clicked. This daily ritual wasn\u2019t just a commute; it was a reset. It was the moment he realized he had plugged himself into the tangible, working soul of the city, finding a deep, physical sense of belonging.\n\n5.\nJust last year, he held a new prototype at work: a surgical device of titanium and polymer. He traced its seamless joints, admiring the precise tolerances. Suddenly, he didn't see a medical tool; he saw the leg of a chair. The same principles of load-bearing, stress distribution, and elegant form applied. His entire career optimizing systems for others was just practice. The dream of his own workshop sharpened into a clear, actionable plan. It was time to engineer something for himself, an object of quiet, lasting utility."
